SIMPLE: west
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: West
<hw>West</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>west</ets>,
adv.; akin to D. <ets>west</ets>, G. <ets>west</ets>, <ets>westen</ets>,
OHG. <ets>westan</ets>, Icel. <ets>vestr</ets>, Sw. <ets>vest</ets>,
<ets>vester</ets>, <ets>vestan</ets>, Dan. <ets>vest</ets>,
<ets>vesten</ets>, and perhaps to L. <ets>vesper</ets> evening, Gr. <?/.
<?/<?/<?/<?/. Cf. <er>Vesper</er>, <er>Visigoth</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The point in the heavens where the sun is seen to
set at the equinox; or, the corresponding point on the earth; that one
of the four cardinal points of the compass which is in a direction at
right angles to that of north and south, and on the left hand of a
person facing north; the point directly opposite to east.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And fresh from the <qex>west</qex> is the free wind's breath.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A country, or region of country, which, with regard
to some other country or region, is situated in the direction toward the
west.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The Western hemisphere,
or the New World so called, it having been discovered by sailing
westward from Europe; the Occident.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(U. S. Hist.
& Geog.)</fld> <def>Formerly, that part of the United States west of the
Alleghany mountains; now, commonly, the whole region west of the
Mississippi river; esp., that part which is north of the Indian
Territory, New Mexico, etc. Usually with the definite article.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>West by north</b></col>, <col><b>West by
south</b></col></mcol>, <cd>according to the notation of the mariner's
compass, that point which lies 11⟦frac14⟧⟦deg⟧ to the north or south,
respectively, of the point due west.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>West
northwest</b></col>, <col><b>West southwest</b></col></mcol>, <cd>that
point which lies 22⟦frac12⟧⟦deg⟧ to the north or south of west, or
halfway between west and northwest or southwest, respectively. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Compass</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>West</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: West
<hw>West</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Lying toward the west;
situated at the west, or in a western direction from the point of
observation or reckoning; proceeding toward the west, or coming from the
west; <as>as, a <ex>west</ex> course is one toward the west; an east and
<ex>west</ex> line; a <ex>west</ex> wind blows from the
west</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This shall be your <qex>west</qex> border.</q> <rj><qau>Num.
xxxiv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>Designating, or situated in, that
part of a church which is opposite to, and farthest from, the east, or
the part containing the chancel and choir.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>West end</b></col>, <cd>the fashionable part of London,
commencing from the east, at Charing Cross.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>West</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: West
<hw>West</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>west</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Westward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>West</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: West
<hw>West</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass to the west; to set, as the sun.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The hot sun gan to <xex>west</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn or move toward the west; to veer from the
north or south toward the west.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Westering</ent>⟦br⟧
